?TOP STORIES

CALIFORNIA'S LARGEST UTILITY CLASHES WITH REGULATORS IN COURT SESSION

Electricity regulators and California's largest utility clashed in Bankruptcy 
Court on Monday in what a state lawyer warned is the first move of a plan to 
wrest control of electric rates from the state's hands.

TEXANS ARE SLOW TO TRY ELECTRICITY SWAP

Texans aren't exactly rushing into electricity deregulation, according to 
state regulators.

FERC EYES POWER PRICE CAPS WESTERN STATES MEET IN BOISE WITH COMMISSION

With generating capacity pushed to the limit and a drought on the horizon 
this summer in the Northwest, federal officials are predicting wholesale 
energy prices will soar even higher and rolling blackouts could become 
commonplace.

360-MEGAWATT MILLENNIUM POWER PLANT ACHIEVES OPERATION STATUS

PG&E National Energy Group, an affiliate of PG&E Corporation today announced 
that its 360-megawatt Millennium Power plant in Charlton, Massachusetts 
achieved commercial operation.

US FERC REJECTS WESTERN AREA POWER ADMINISTRATION'S BID TO SUPPLY POWER TO 
DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY LAB IN NEW MEXICO

Federal regulators Thursday rejected an attempt by a U.S. nuclear weapons 
laboratory in New Mexico to obtain electricity supplies from a federal power 
marketing agency.


